{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"52b5c4d3-58d8-4036-b49d-2b740b91e9fe","content":"Here's how to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on Kubernetes:\n\n### 1. Exec into the container\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n### 2. Install `dotnet-trace` (if not already present)\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n### 3. Find your process ID\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n### 4. Collect the trace\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n### Getting the file out\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-trace-file> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n### Alternative: `dotnet-counters` for a quick look first\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-counters\ndotnet-counters monitor -p <PID> --counters System.Runtime\n```\nThis gives a live view of CPU %, GC, threadpool stats — useful before committing to a full trace.\n\n> **Tip:** If `dotnet tool install` fails due to no SDK in the container, you can download the standalone `dotnet-trace` from the [.NET diagnostics releases](https://github.com/dotnet/diagnostics) or use `perfcollect`/ETW tracing from the host with admin access.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c02270cf-6a47-49af-9582-40d87752d779","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes, where they're experiencing high CPU. This is a troubleshooting/advisory question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise guidance.","outputTokens":442,"requestId":"AC0E:37A40F:137C74B:15E05B7:6A066FE5"},"id":"9535c882-9540-4f0d-bfbc-15bb4747042e","timestamp":"2026-05-15T00:59:27.636Z","parentId":"80aa2c47-5f83-457f-b124-e1e20ccc9701"}
